## Employment and Financial Survival  

| Strategy                        | Description                                                                                         | Challenges                                                       |
|--------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------|
| Criminal Activity              | Drug dealing, theft, fraud, pimping, or other illegal means to generate income                   | High risk of arrest, violence, and exploitation                  |
| Informal Cash Jobs             | Day labor, agricultural work, construction, or other cash-based employment                        | Limited job security, low pay, and potential exposure            |
| Online Work                   | Affiliate marketing, freelance work using anonymous accounts                                     | Requires internet access and technical skills                    |
| Living Off Savings or Support | Using saved money or support from trusted individuals                                            | Unsustainable long-term, risk of betrayal                        |

Most fugitives rely on criminal activities due to the difficulty of obtaining legitimate employment without proper identification. However, some manage to find under-the-table jobs in industries accustomed to undocumented or transient workers, such as agriculture or construction ([Mixon, 2017](https://www.quora.com/How-does-a-fugitive-survive-without-a-proper-job)).  

---

## Common Mistakes Leading to Capture  

Despite careful planning, many fugitives are eventually caught due to:  

- **Laundry and Personal Hygiene:** Using public laundromats exposes fugitives to surveillance and stakeouts ([Mixon, 2021](https://www.quora.com/What-are-the-most-common-mistakes-that-fugitives-on-the-run-make-that-lead-to-their-capture)).  
- **Roots in Small Communities:** Moving to small towns where newcomers attract attention ([Mixon, 2021](https://www.quora.com/What-are-the-most-common-mistakes-that-fugitives-on-the-run-make-that-lead-to-their-capture)).  
- **Contacting Family or Friends:** Maintaining relationships can lead to betrayal or inadvertent disclosure ([Mixon, 2022](https://www.quora.com/How-do-fugitives-normally-get-caught-years-after-while-on-the-run)).  
- **Complacency:** Over time, fugitives may become careless or complacent, increasing risk ([Tarte, 2022](https://www.quora.com/How-do-fugitives-normally-get-caught-years-after-while-on-the-run)).  
- **Digital Footprints:** Use of phones, social media, or financial transactions can be traced ([Brown, 2017](https://www.vice.com/en/article/7xq4w4/current-and-former-fugitives-talk-about-being-on-the-run-from-police)).  

